Horace was himself the son of a freedman, but nothing could be more offensive to him than the straining and display of such parvenus. His own attitude is clearly seen in S. 1, 6, where his calm tone shows that he is discussing a general question. The fierceness of this epode seems to warrant the belief that he has some definite individual in mind, who probably was easily recognized by his contemporaries. All efforts to identify him are useless. Many of the MSS. have , the inscription: ad Sextum Menam Lz'bertinum. Vedium Rufum ex servitute miratur usurpasse equestrem dignitatem nsque ad tribu— natum militum. The first part refers to Menas, or Menodorus, a freedman of Sextus Pompey who twice deserted to Octavian. The name Vedius was probably suggested to the earlier commentators by a passage in Cicero's letter to Atticus (ad Att. 6, 1, 2 5) which was written at Laodicea in 54 Bc, but not published until some time in the first
